//@ exit: 101

// A trap is an effect, whether or not anyone reads the value.
//
// `xs[10]` here is a statement: nothing consumes the element. Dead-code elimination
// removed the whole instruction on the grounds that its result was unused, and removed the
// bounds check with it — so this program ran clean past the end of a three-element list and
// exited 0. The same held for `1 / 0` and `1 % 0` as statements, while the identical
// expressions trapped correctly the moment their results were used.
//
// The effect analysis classified everything that was not a call as pure. A trap ends the
// program, which is about as observable as an effect gets, so indexing and the i64
// arithmetic that can overflow or divide by zero are effectful regardless of what happens
// to the result.
//
// The exit code is the point of the test: 101 means the trap fired. A 0 here is the bug.

use std::io;

fn main() {
    let xs = [1, 2, 3];
    io::println("before");
    xs[10];
    io::println("unreachable: the index above traps");
}
